HE USED to cut people’s hair at a salon but now, he’s living his childhood dream of being a TV presenter and producer. In 2019, Adeniyi Lawal put down his scissors to focus on his passion and it has paid off. The 48-year-old from Randburg, Joburg, told Daily Sun when he quit cutting people’s hair, he knew his destiny was to be in the TV industry. He encouraged others not to give up on their dreams. “My dream was to become an established TV host and have a production house to help Africa as a whole,” he said. Adeniyi, who is also an artist, said he was working on Soweto TV’s show Gold and City Muzik Francophone. Adeniyi, who is originally from Togo in West Africa, said he worked in TV production in his home country before moving to South Africa in 2013. He said Gold, which started airing in 2021, told stories of resilience to inspire people. Adeniyi said: “City Muzik Francophone, which started almost a month ago, is an entertainment show where we play music videos from French-speaking countries in Africa. ,” he said. “We entertain and educate people about former French colonies in Africa. It serves as a bridge between English and French Africa. ” “We want to educate, entertain and showcase our African talents through telling our own stories.” said his aim was to teach Africans more about the continent’s culture and music. He added: “We still want to bring Africans together for a festival, gala dinner and awards nights. “These will be a collaboration between African artists and other people in the arts and culture. “We want to work together to build a stronger Africa for the next generation.”